1. Can you explain the differences among these three concepts (CI/CD)?

EXPLAIN IN THIS ANSWER:-
â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”
CICD Stands for Continuos Integration(CI) & Continuos Delivery/Deployment(CD).
ğŸ”¹ Continuous Integration (CI):
ğŸ‘‰ Developers frequently push code changes (e.g., a new discount feature).
ğŸ‘‰ A CI pipline (Jenkins, GitHub Actions, GitLab CI/CD) automatically builds the code, runs tests, and performs security scans.
ğŸ‘‰ If everything passes, the code is merged into the main branch.

ğŸ”¹ Continuous Delivery (CD):
ğŸ‘‰ The application is automatically deployed to a staging environment for manual review.
ğŸ‘‰ Once approved, it's ready for production deployment.

ğŸ”¹ Continuous Deployment (CD):
ğŸ‘‰ If fully automated, the changes go directly to production after passing tests.
ğŸ‘‰ Using blue-green or canary deployments, the update is rolled out with zero downtime.
ğŸ‘‰ If an issue is found, an auto-rollback mechanism restores the previous version.
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

2. What CI/CD tool have you worked with, which one do you prefer?â€‹

EXPLAIN IN THIS ANSWER:-
â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”
ğŸ”¹ Jenkins is an open-source automation server used to implement CI/CD pipelines in DevOps. 
  It automates building, testing, and deploying applications, making software delivery faster and more reliable.

ğŸ”¥ I Preferred Jenkins (For On-Prem & Hybrid Cloud CI/CD):
ğŸ‘‰ Highly customizable and integrates well with on-prem infrastructure.
ğŸ‘‰ Supports pipeline as code (Jenkinsfile), making it easy to automate builds.
ğŸ‘‰ Works well with Maven, SonarQube, Trivy, Docker, Kubernetes, and AWS EKS.
